
@@libJob 
</br>1 :
</br>1 -
</br>22 
<p></p>
</br>1 There happened to be a man in the land of Uz whose name was Job; and that man proved to be blameless and upright, and fearing God and turning aside from bad.
</br>2 And seven sons and three daughters came to be born to him.
</br>3 And his livestock got to be seven thousand sheep and three thousand camels and five hundred spans of cattle and five hundred she-asses, along with a very large body of servants; and that man came to be the greatest of all the Orientals.
<p></p>
</br>4 And his sons went and held a banquet at the house of each one on his own day; and they sent and invited their three sisters to eat and drink with them.
</br>5 And it would occur that when the banquet days had gone round the circuit, Job would send and sanctify them; and he got up early in the morning and offered up burnt sacrifices according to the number of all of them; for, said Job, “maybe my sons have sinned and have cursed God in their heart.” That is the way Job would do always.
<p></p>
</br>6 Now it came to be the day when the sons of the [true] God entered to take their station before Jehovah, and even Satan proceeded to enter right among them.
<p></p>
</br>7 Then Jehovah said to Satan: “Where do you come from?” At that Satan answered Jehovah and said: “From roving about in the earth and from walking about in it.”
</br>8 And Jehovah went on to say to Satan: “Have you set your heart upon my servant Job, that there is no one like him in the earth, a man blameless and upright, fearing God and turning aside from bad?”
</br>9 At that Satan answered Jehovah and said: “Is it for nothing that Job has feared God?
</br>10 Have not you yourself put up a hedge about him and about his house and about everything that he has all around? The work of his hands you have blessed, and his livestock itself has spread abroad in the earth.
</br>11 But, for a change, thrust out your hand, please, and touch everything he has [and see] whether he will not curse you to your very face.”
</br>12 Accordingly Jehovah said to Satan: “Look! Everything that he has is in your hand. Only against him himself do not thrust out your hand!” So Satan went out away from the person of Jehovah.
<p></p>
</br>13 Now it came to be the day when his sons and his daughters were eating and drinking wine in the house of their brother the firstborn.
</br>14 And there came a messenger to Job, and he proceeded to say: “The cattle themselves happened to be plowing and the she-asses were grazing at the side of them
</br>15 when the Sa·be´ans came making a raid and taking them, and the attendants they struck down with the edge of the sword; and I got to escape, only I by myself, to tell you.”
<p></p>
</br>16 While this one was yet speaking that one came and proceeded to say: “The very fire of God fell from the heavens and went blazing among the sheep and the attendants and eating them up; and I got to escape, only I by myself, to tell you.”
<p></p>
</br>17 While that one was yet speaking another one came and proceeded to say: “The Chal·de´ans made up three bands and went dashing against the camels and taking them, and the attendants they struck down with the edge of the sword; and I got to escape, only I by myself, to tell you.”
<p></p>
</br>18 While this other one was yet speaking, still another one came and proceeded to say: “Your sons and your daughters were eating and drinking wine in the house of their brother the firstborn.
</br>19 And, look! there came a great wind from the region of the wilderness, and it went striking the four corners of the house, so that it fell upon the young people and they died. And I got to escape, only I by myself, to tell you.”
<p></p>
</br>20 And Job proceeded to get up and rip his sleeveless coat apart and cut the hair off his head and fall to the earth and bow down
</br>21 and say:
@@citp“Naked I came out of my mother’s belly,
@@citzAnd naked shall I return there.
@@citpJehovah himself has given, and Jehovah himself has taken away.
@@citzLet the name of Jehovah continue to be blessed.”
<p></p>
</br>22 In all this Job did not sin or ascribe anything improper to God.
@@libJob 
</br>2 :
</br>1 -
</br>13 
<p></p>
</br>1 Afterward it came to be the day when the sons of the [true] God entered to take their station before Jehovah, and Satan also proceeded to enter right among them to take his station before Jehovah.
<p></p>
</br>2 Then Jehovah said to Satan: “Just where do you come from?” At that Satan answered Jehovah and said: “From roving about in the earth and from walking about in it.”
</br>3 And Jehovah went on to say to Satan: “Have you set your heart upon my servant Job, that there is no one like him in the earth, a man blameless and upright, fearing God and turning aside from bad? Even yet he is holding fast his integrity, although you incite me against him to swallow him up without cause.”
</br>4 But Satan answered Jehovah and said: “Skin in behalf of skin, and everything that a man has he will give in behalf of his soul.
</br>5 For a change, thrust out your hand, please, and touch as far as his bone and his flesh [and see] whether he will not curse you to your very face.”
<p></p>
</br>6 Accordingly Jehovah said to Satan: “There he is in your hand! Only watch out for his soul itself!”
</br>7 So Satan went out away from the person of Jehovah and struck Job with a malignant boil from the sole of his foot to the crown of his head.
</br>8 And he proceeded to take for himself a fragment of earthenware with which to scrape himself; and he was sitting in among the ashes.
<p></p>
</br>9 Finally his wife said to him: “Are you yet holding fast your integrity? Curse God and die!”
</br>10 But he said to her: “As one of the senseless women speaks, you speak also. Shall we accept merely what is good from the [true] God and not accept also what is bad?” In all this Job did not sin with his lips.
<p></p>
</br>11 And three companions of Job got to hear of all this calamity that had come upon him, and they proceeded to come, each one from his own place, El´i·phaz the Te´man·ite and Bil´dad the Shu´hite and Zo´phar the Na´a·ma·thite. So they met together by appointment to come and sympathize with him and comfort him.
</br>12 When they raised their eyes from far off they did not then recognize him. And they proceeded to raise their voice and weep and rip each one his sleeveless coat apart and toss dust toward the heavens upon their heads.
</br>13 And they kept sitting with him on the earth seven days and seven nights, and there was no one speaking a word to him, for they saw that the pain was very great.
@@libJob 
</br>3 :
</br>1 -
</br>26 
<p></p>
</br>1 It was after this that Job opened his mouth and began to call down evil upon his day.
</br>2 Job now answered and said:
<p></p>
</br>3 “Let the day perish on which I came to be born,
@@citzAlso the night that someone said, ‘An able-bodied man has been conceived!’
<p></p>
</br>4 As for that day, let it become darkness.
@@citzLet not God look for it from above,
@@citzNor let daylight beam upon it.
<p></p>
</br>5 Let darkness and deep shadow reclaim it.
@@citzLet a rain cloud reside over it.
@@citzLet the things that darken a day terrorize it.
<p></p>
</br>6 That night—let gloom take it;
@@citzLet it not feel glad among the days of a year;
@@citzAmong the number of the lunar months let it not enter.
<p></p>
</br>7 Look! That night—let it become sterile;
@@citzLet no joyful cry come in it.
<p></p>
</br>8 Let cursers of the day execrate it,
@@citzThose ready to awaken Le·vi´a·than.
<p></p>
</br>9 Let the stars of its twilight grow dark;
@@citzLet it wait for the light and there be none;
@@citzAnd let it not see the beams of dawn.
<p></p>
</br>10 For it did not close the doors of my [mother’s] belly,
@@citzAnd so conceal trouble from my eyes.
<p></p>
</br>11 Why from the womb did I not proceed to die?
@@citz[Why did I not] come forth from the belly itself and then expire?
<p></p>
</br>12 Why was it that knees confronted me,
@@citzAnd why breasts that I should take suck?
<p></p>
</br>13 For by now I should have lain down that I might be undisturbed;
@@citzI should have slept then; I should be at rest
<p></p>
</br>14 With kings and counselors of the earth,
@@citzThose building desolate places for themselves,
<p></p>
</br>15 Or with princes who have gold,
@@citzThose who fill their houses with silver;
<p></p>
</br>16 Or, like a hidden miscarriage, I should not come to be,
@@citzLike children that have seen no light.
<p></p>
</br>17 There the wicked themselves have ceased from agitation,
@@citzAnd there those weary in power are at rest.
<p></p>
</br>18 Together prisoners themselves are at ease;
@@citzThey actually do not hear the voice of one driving them to work.
<p></p>
</br>19 Small and great are there the same,
@@citzAnd the slave is set free from his master.
<p></p>
</br>20 Why does he give light to one having trouble,
@@citzAnd life to those bitter of soul?
<p></p>
</br>21 Why are there those waiting for death, and it is not,
@@citzAlthough they keep digging for it more than for hidden treasures?
<p></p>
</br>22 Those who are rejoicing to gleefulness,
@@citzThey exult because they find a burial place.
<p></p>
</br>23 [Why does he give light] to able-bodied man, whose way has been concealed,
@@citzAnd whom God hedges in?
<p></p>
</br>24 For before my food my sighing comes,
@@citzAnd like waters my roaring cries pour forth;
<p></p>
</br>25 Because a dreadful thing I have dreaded, and it comes upon me;
@@citzAnd what I have been scared of comes to me.
<p></p>
</br>26 I have not been carefree, nor have I been undisturbed,
@@citzNor been at rest, and yet agitation comes.”
@@libJob 
</br>4 :
</br>1 -
</br>21 
<p></p>
</br>1 And El´i·phaz the Te´man·ite proceeded to reply and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “If one does try out a word to you, will you become weary?
@@citzBut to put a restraint on words who is able?
<p></p>
</br>3 Look! You have corrected many,
@@citzAnd the weak hands you used to strengthen.
<p></p>
</br>4 Anyone stumbling, your words would raise up;
@@citzAnd knees giving way you would make firm.
<p></p>
</br>5 But this time it comes to you, and you become weary;
@@citzIt touches even you, and you get disturbed.
<p></p>
</br>6 Is not your reverence [the basis of] your confidence?
@@citzIs not your hope even the integrity of your ways?
<p></p>
</br>7 Remember, please: Who that is innocent has ever perished?
@@citzAnd where have the upright ever been effaced?
<p></p>
</br>8 According to what I have seen, those devising what is hurtful
@@citzAnd those sowing trouble will themselves reap it.
<p></p>
</br>9 Through the breath of God they perish,
@@citzAnd through the spirit of his anger they come to an end.
<p></p>
</br>10 There is the roaring of a lion, and the voice of a young lion,
@@citzBut the teeth of maned young lions do get broken down.
<p></p>
</br>11 A lion is perishing from there being no prey,
@@citzAnd the cubs of a lion are separated from one another.
<p></p>
</br>12 Now to me a word was stealthily brought,
@@citzAnd my ear proceeded to get a whisper of it,
<p></p>
</br>13 In disquieting thoughts from visions of the night,
@@citzWhen deep sleep falls upon men.
<p></p>
</br>14 A dread came over me, and a trembling,
@@citzAnd the multitude of my bones it filled with dread.
<p></p>
</br>15 And a spirit itself went passing over my face;
@@citzThe hair of my flesh began to bristle.
<p></p>
</br>16 It began to stand still,
@@citzBut I did not recognize its appearance;
@@citpA form was in front of my eyes;
@@citzThere was a calm, and I now heard a voice:
<p></p>
</br>17 ‘Mortal man—can he be more just than God himself?
@@citzOr can able-bodied man be cleaner than his own Maker?’
<p></p>
</br>18 Look! In his servants he has no faith,
@@citzAnd his messengers he charges with faultiness.
<p></p>
</br>19 How much more so with those dwelling in houses of clay,
@@citzWhose foundation is in the dust!
@@citzOne crushes them more quickly than a moth.
<p></p>
</br>20 From morning to evening they are crushed to pieces;
@@citzWithout anyone’s taking [it to heart] they perish forever.
<p></p>
</br>21 Has not their tent cord within them been pulled out?
@@citzThey die for lack of wisdom.
@@libJob 
</br>5 :
</br>1 -
</br>27 
<p></p>
</br>1 “Call, please! Is there anyone answering you?
@@citzAnd to which one of the holy ones will you turn?
<p></p>
</br>2 For the foolish one vexation will kill,
@@citzAnd the one easily enticed envying will put to death.
<p></p>
</br>3 I myself have seen the foolish one taking root,
@@citzBut suddenly I began to execrate his abiding place.
<p></p>
</br>4 His sons remain far from salvation,
@@citzAnd they are crushed in the gate without a deliverer.
<p></p>
</br>5 What he harvests the hungry one eats;
@@citzAnd even from butcher hooks one takes it,
@@citzAnd a snare actually snaps at their means of maintenance.
<p></p>
</br>6 For not from mere dust does what is hurtful go forth,
@@citzAnd from mere ground trouble does not spring up.
<p></p>
</br>7 For man himself is born for trouble,
@@citzAs the very sparks fly upward.
<p></p>
</br>8 However, I myself would apply to God,
@@citzAnd to God I would submit my cause,
<p></p>
</br>9 [To the] One doing great things unsearchable,
@@citzWonderful things without number;
<p></p>
</br>10 [To] the One giving rain upon the surface of the earth
@@citzAnd sending waters upon the open fields;
<p></p>
</br>11 [To] the One putting those who are low on a high place,
@@citzSo that those who are sad are high up in salvation;
<p></p>
</br>12 [To the] One frustrating the schemes of the shrewd,
@@citzSo that their hands do not work with effect;
<p></p>
</br>13 [To the] One catching the wise in their own cunning,
@@citzSo that the counsel of astute ones is carried headlong;
<p></p>
</br>14 They encounter darkness even by day,
@@citzAnd they grope about at midday as if at night;
<p></p>
</br>15 And [to the] One saving from the sword out of their mouth,
@@citzAnd from the hand of the strong one, a poor one,
<p></p>
</br>16 So that for the lowly one there comes to be hope,
@@citzBut unrighteousness actually shuts its mouth.
<p></p>
</br>17 Look! Happy is the man whom God reproves;
@@citzAnd the discipline of the Almighty do not you reject!
<p></p>
</br>18 For he himself causes pain, but binds up [the wound];
@@citzHe breaks to pieces, but his own hands do the healing.
<p></p>
</br>19 In six distresses he will deliver you,
@@citzAnd in seven nothing injurious will touch you.
<p></p>
</br>20 During famine he will certainly redeem you from death,
@@citzAnd during war from the power of a sword.
<p></p>
</br>21 From the whip of a tongue you will be hidden,
@@citzAnd you will not be afraid of despoiling when it comes.
<p></p>
</br>22 At despoiling and hunger you will laugh,
@@citzAnd of the wild beast of the earth you need not be afraid.
<p></p>
</br>23 For with the stones of the field your covenant will be,
@@citzAnd the wild beast of the field himself will be made to live at peace with you.
<p></p>
</br>24 And you will certainly know that peace itself is your tent,
@@citzAnd you will be bound to go and see your pasture ground, and you will miss nothing.
<p></p>
</br>25 And you will certainly know that your offspring are many
@@citzAnd your descendants like the vegetation of the earth.
<p></p>
</br>26 You will come in vigor to the burial place,
@@citzAs when sheaves pile up in their time.
<p></p>
</br>27 Look! This is what we have investigated. So is it.
@@citzHear it, and you—know it for yourself.”
@@libJob 
</br>6 :
</br>1 -
</br>30 
<p></p>
</br>1 And Job proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “O that my vexation were altogether weighed,
@@citzAnd that at the same time my adversity they would put on scales themselves!
<p></p>
</br>3 For now it is heavier even than the sands of the seas.
@@citzThat is why my own words have been wild talk.
<p></p>
</br>4 For the arrows of the Almighty are with me,
@@citzThe venom of which my spirit is drinking;
@@citzThe terrors from God range themselves up against me.
<p></p>
</br>5 Will a zebra cry out over grass,
@@citzOr a bull low over its fodder?
<p></p>
</br>6 Will tasteless things be eaten without salt,
@@citzOr is there any taste in the slimy juice of marshmallow?
<p></p>
</br>7 My soul has refused to touch [anything].
@@citzThey are like disease in my food.
<p></p>
</br>8 O that my request would come
@@citzAnd that God would grant even my hope!
<p></p>
</br>9 And that God would go ahead and crush me,
@@citzThat he would release his hand and cut me off!
<p></p>
</br>10 Even it would still be my comfort;
@@citzAnd I should leap [for joy] at [my] labor pains,
@@citz[Though] he would have no compassion, for I have not hidden the sayings of the Holy One.
<p></p>
</br>11 What is my power, that I should keep waiting?
@@citzAnd what is my end, that I should keep prolonging my soul?
<p></p>
</br>12 Is my power the power of stones?
@@citzOr is my flesh of copper?
<p></p>
</br>13 Is it that self-assistance is not in me,
@@citzAnd effectual working itself has been chased away from me?
<p></p>
</br>14 As regards anyone who withholds loving-kindness from his own fellow,
@@citzHe will also leave off even the fear of the Almighty.
<p></p>
</br>15 My own brothers have dealt treacherously, like a winter torrent,
@@citzLike the channel of winter torrents that keep passing away.
<p></p>
</br>16 They are dark from ice,
@@citzUpon them snow hides itself.
<p></p>
</br>17 In due season they become waterless, they have been silenced;
@@citzWhen it grows hot they are dried up from their place.
<p></p>
</br>18 The paths of their way are turned aside;
@@citzThey go up into the empty place and perish.
<p></p>
</br>19 The caravans of Te´ma have looked,
@@citzThe traveling company of Sa·be´ans have waited for them.
<p></p>
</br>20 They certainly are ashamed because they had trusted;
@@citzThey have come clear to the place and they get disappointed.
<p></p>
</br>21 For now YOU men have amounted to nothing;
@@citzYOU see terror, and YOU become afraid.
<p></p>
</br>22 Is it because I have said, ‘GIVE me [something],
@@citzOr from some of the power of YOU men make a present in my behalf;
<p></p>
</br>23 And rescue me out of the hand of an adversary,
@@citzAnd out of the hand of tyrants YOU men should redeem me’?
<p></p>
</br>24 Instruct me, and I, for my part, shall be silent;
@@citzAnd what mistake I have committed make me understand.
<p></p>
</br>25 The sayings of uprightness have been—O not painful!
@@citzBut what does reproving on the part of YOU men reprove?
<p></p>
</br>26 Is it to reprove words that YOU men scheme,
@@citzWhen the sayings of one in despair are for mere wind?
<p></p>
</br>27 How much more will YOU cast lots even over someone fatherless,
@@citzAnd barter over YOUR companion!
<p></p>
</br>28 And now GO ahead, pay attention to me,
@@citz[And see] whether I shall lie to YOUR very faces.
<p></p>
</br>29 Return, please—let no unrighteousness arise—
@@citzYes, return—my righteousness is yet in it.
<p></p>
</br>30 Is there unrighteousness on my tongue,
@@citzOr does my own palate not discern adversity?
@@libJob 
</br>7 :
</br>1 -
</br>21 
<p></p>
</br>1 “Is there not a compulsory labor for mortal man on earth,
@@citzAnd are not his days like the days of a hired laborer?
<p></p>
</br>2 Like a slave he pants for the shadow,
@@citzAnd like a hired laborer he waits for his wages.
<p></p>
</br>3 Thus I have been made to possess worthless lunar months,
@@citzAnd nights of trouble they have counted out to me.
<p></p>
</br>4 When I have lain down I have also said, ‘When shall I get up?’
@@citzAnd [when] evening actually goes its measure, I have also been glutted with restlessness until morning twilight.
<p></p>
</br>5 My flesh has become clothed with maggots and lumps of dust;
@@citzMy skin itself has formed crusts and dissolves.
<p></p>
</br>6 My days themselves have become swifter than a weaver’s shuttle,
@@citzAnd they come to an end in hopelessness.
<p></p>
</br>7 Remember that my life is wind;
@@citzThat my eye will not see good again.
<p></p>
</br>8 The eye of him that sees me will not behold me;
@@citzYour eyes will be upon me, but I shall not be.
<p></p>
</br>9 The cloud certainly comes to its end and goes away;
@@citzSo he that is going down to She´ol will not come up.
<p></p>
</br>10 He will not return anymore to his house,
@@citzAnd his place will not acknowledge him anymore.
<p></p>
</br>11 I, also, I shall not hold back my mouth.
@@citzI will speak in the distress of my spirit;
@@citzI will be concerned with the bitterness of my soul!
<p></p>
</br>12 Am I a sea or a sea monster,
@@citzThat you should set a guard over me?
<p></p>
</br>13 When I said, ‘My divan will comfort me,
@@citzMy bed will help carry my concern,’
<p></p>
</br>14 You even have terrified me with dreams,
@@citzAnd by visions you make me start up in fright,
<p></p>
</br>15 So that my soul chooses suffocation,
@@citzDeath rather than my bones.
<p></p>
</br>16 I have rejected [it]; to time indefinite I would not live.
@@citzCease from me, for my days are an exhalation.
<p></p>
</br>17 What is mortal man that you should rear him,
@@citzAnd that you should set your heart upon him,
<p></p>
</br>18 And that you should pay attention to him every morning,
@@citzThat every moment you should test him?
<p></p>
</br>19 Why will you not turn your gaze from me,
@@citzNor let me alone until I swallow my saliva?
<p></p>
</br>20 If I have sinned, what can I accomplish against you, the Observer of mankind?
@@citzWhy is it that you have set me as your target, so that I should become a burden to you?
<p></p>
</br>21 And why do you not pardon my transgression
@@citzAnd overlook my error?
@@citpFor now in dust I shall lie down;
@@citzAnd you will certainly look for me, and I shall not be.”
