</br>22 
<p></p>
</br>1 And Bil´dad the Shu´hite proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “How long will you keep uttering these things,
@@citzWhen the sayings of your mouth are but a powerful wind?
<p></p>
</br>3 Will God himself pervert judgment,
@@citzOr will the Almighty himself pervert righteousness?
<p></p>
</br>4 If your own sons have sinned against him,
@@citzSo that he lets them go into the hand of their revolt,
<p></p>
</br>5 If you yourself will look for God,
@@citzAnd [if] of the Almighty you will implore favor,
<p></p>
</br>6 If you are pure and upright,
@@citzBy now he would awake for you
@@citzAnd he would certainly restore your righteous abiding place.
<p></p>
</br>7 Also, your beginning may have proved to be a small thing,
@@citzBut your own end afterward would grow very great.
<p></p>
</br>8 Indeed, ask, please, of the former generation,
@@citzAnd direct [your attention] to the things searched out by their fathers.
<p></p>
</br>9 For we were only yesterday, and we know nothing,
@@citzBecause our days on earth are a shadow.
<p></p>
</br>10 Will not they themselves instruct you, tell you,
@@citzAnd from their heart will they not bring forth words?
<p></p>
</br>11 Will a papyrus plant grow tall without a swampy place?
@@citzWill a reed grow big without water?
<p></p>
</br>12 While it is yet in its bud, not plucked off,
@@citzEven ahead of all other grass it will dry up.
<p></p>
</br>13 Thus are the pathways of all those forgetting God,
@@citzAnd the very hope of an apostate will perish,
<p></p>
</br>14 Whose confidence is cut off,
@@citzAnd whose trust is a spider’s house.
<p></p>
</br>15 He will lean upon his house, but it will not keep standing;
@@citzHe will take hold of it, but it will not last.
<p></p>
</br>16 He is full of sap before the sun,
@@citzAnd in his garden his own twig goes forth.
<p></p>
</br>17 In a stone heap his roots become interwoven,
@@citzA house of stones he beholds.
<p></p>
</br>18 If one swallows him up from his place,
@@citzIt will also certainly deny him, [saying,] ‘I have not seen you.’
<p></p>
</br>19 Look! That is the dissolving of his way;
@@citzAnd from the dust others spring up.
<p></p>
</br>20 Look! God himself will not reject anyone blameless,
@@citzNeither will he take hold of the hand of evildoers,
<p></p>
</br>21 Until he fills your mouth with laughter,
@@citzAnd your lips with joyful shouting.
<p></p>
</br>22 The very ones hating you will be clothed with shame,
@@citzAnd the tent of wicked ones will not be.”
@@libJob 
</br>9 :
</br>1 -
</br>35 
<p></p>
</br>1 And Job proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “For a fact I do know that it is so.
@@citzBut how can mortal man be in the right in a case with God?
<p></p>
</br>3 If he should find delight in contending with him,
@@citzHe cannot answer him once out of a thousand.
<p></p>
</br>4 He is wise in heart and strong in power.
@@citzWho can show stubbornness to him and come off uninjured?
<p></p>
</br>5 He is moving mountains away, so that people do not even know [of them],
@@citzHe who has overthrown them in his anger.
<p></p>
</br>6 He is making the earth go quaking from its place,
@@citzSo that its very pillars shudder.
<p></p>
</br>7 He is saying to the sun that it should not shine forth,
@@citzAnd around stars he puts a seal,
<p></p>
</br>8 Stretching out the heavens by himself
@@citzAnd treading upon the high waves of the sea;
<p></p>
</br>9 Making the Ash constellation, the Ke´sil constellation,
@@citzAnd the Ki´mah constellation and the interior rooms of the South;
<p></p>
</br>10 Doing great things unsearchable,
@@citzAnd wonderful things without number.
<p></p>
</br>11 Look! He passes by me and I do not see [him],
@@citzAnd he moves on and I do not discern him.
<p></p>
</br>12 Look! He snatches away. Who can resist him?
@@citzWho will say to him, ‘What are you doing?’
<p></p>
</br>13 God himself will not turn back his anger;
@@citzBeneath him the helpers of a stormer must bow down.
<p></p>
</br>14 How much more so in case I myself answer him!
@@citzI will choose my words with him,
<p></p>
</br>15 Whom I would not answer, even though I were really in the right.
@@citzOf my opponent-at-law I would implore favor.
<p></p>
</br>16 If I called him, would he answer me?
@@citzI do not believe that he would give ear to my voice;
<p></p>
</br>17 Who with a storm bruises me
@@citzAnd certainly makes my wounds many for no reason.
<p></p>
</br>18 He will not grant me my taking of a fresh breath,
@@citzFor he keeps glutting me with bitter things.
<p></p>
</br>19 If in power anyone is strong, there [he is];
@@citzAnd if in justice [anyone is strong], O that I may be summoned!
<p></p>
</br>20 If I were in the right, my own mouth would pronounce me wicked;
@@citzWere I blameless, then he would declare me crooked.
<p></p>
</br>21 Were I blameless, I would not know my soul;
@@citzI would refuse my life.
<p></p>
</br>22 One thing there is. That is why I do say,
@@citz‘One blameless, also a wicked one, he is bringing to their end.’
<p></p>
</br>23 If a flash flood itself should cause death suddenly,
@@citzAt the very despair of the innocent ones he would mock.
<p></p>
</br>24 Earth itself has been given into the hand of the wicked one;
@@citzThe face of its judges he covers.
@@citzIf not, who, then, is it?
<p></p>
</br>25 Also my own days have become swifter than a runner;
@@citzThey have run away, they will certainly not see good.
<p></p>
</br>26 They have moved on like reed boats,
@@citzLike an eagle that darts to and fro for something to eat.
<p></p>
</br>27 If I have said, ‘Let me forget my concern,
@@citzLet me alter my countenance and brighten up,’
<p></p>
</br>28 I have been scared of all my pains;
@@citzI do know that you will not hold me innocent.
<p></p>
</br>29 I myself am to become wicked.
@@citzWhy is it that I toil merely in vain?
<p></p>
</br>30 If I actually washed myself in snow water,
@@citzAnd I actually cleansed my hands in potash,
<p></p>
</br>31 Then in a pit you would dip me,
@@citzAnd my garments would certainly detest me.
<p></p>
</br>32 For he is not a man like me [that] I should answer him,
@@citzThat we should come together in judgment.
<p></p>
</br>33 There exists no person to decide between us,
@@citzThat he should put his hand upon both of us.
<p></p>
</br>34 Let him remove his rod from upon me,
@@citzAnd his frightfulness, let it not terrify me.
<p></p>
</br>35 Let me speak and not be afraid of him,
@@citzFor I am not so disposed in myself.
