<p></p>
</br>1 “My soul certainly feels a loathing toward my life.
@@citzI will give vent to my concern about myself.
@@citzI will speak in the bitterness of my soul!
<p></p>
</br>2 I shall say to God, ‘Do not pronounce me wicked.
@@citzCause me to know why it is that you are contending with me.
<p></p>
</br>3 Is it good for you that you should do wrong,
@@citzThat you should reject [the product of] the hard work of your hands,
@@citzAnd that upon the counsel of wicked ones you should actually beam?
<p></p>
</br>4 Do you have eyes of flesh,
@@citzOr is it as a mortal man sees that you see?
<p></p>
</br>5 Are your days like the days of mortal man,
@@citzOr your years just like the days of an able-bodied man,
<p></p>
</br>6 That you should try to find my error
@@citzAnd for my sin you should keep looking?
<p></p>
</br>7 This in spite of your own knowledge that I am not in the wrong,
@@citzAnd there is no one delivering out of your own hand?
<p></p>
</br>8 Your own hands have shaped me so that they made me
@@citzIn entirety round about, and yet you would swallow me up.
<p></p>
</br>9 Remember, please, that out of clay you have made me
@@citzAnd to dust you will make me return.
<p></p>
</br>10 Did you not proceed to pour me out as milk itself
@@citzAnd like cheese to curdle me?
<p></p>
</br>11 With skin and flesh you proceeded to clothe me
@@citzAnd with bones and sinews to weave me together.
<p></p>
</br>12 Life and loving-kindness you have worked with me;
@@citzAnd your own care has guarded my spirit.
<p></p>
</br>13 And these things you have concealed in your heart.
@@citzI well know that these things are with you.
<p></p>
</br>14 If I have sinned and you have kept watching me
@@citzAnd of my error you do not hold me innocent;
<p></p>
</br>15 If I am actually in the wrong, too bad for me!
@@citzAnd [if] I am actually in the right, I may not raise my head,
@@citzGlutted with dishonor and saturated with affliction.
<p></p>
</br>16 And [if] it acts haughtily, like a young lion you will hunt for me,
@@citzAnd you will again show yourself marvelous in my case.
<p></p>
</br>17 You will bring forth new witnesses of yours in front of me,
@@citzAnd you will make your vexation with me greater;
@@citzHardship after hardship is with me.
<p></p>
</br>18 So why from a womb did you bring me out?
@@citzCould I have expired, that not even an eye could see me,
<p></p>
</br>19 There as though I had not come to be I should have become;
@@citzFrom the belly to the burial place I should have been brought.’
<p></p>
</br>20 Are not my days few? Let him leave off,
@@citzLet him turn his gaze from me, that I may brighten up a little
<p></p>
</br>21 Before I go away—and I shall not come back—
@@citzTo the land of darkness and deep shadow,
<p></p>
</br>22 To the land of obscurity like gloom, of deep shadow
@@citzAnd disorder, where it beams no more than gloom does.”
