<p></p>
</br>1 And Zo´phar the Na´a·ma·thite proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “Will a multitude of words go unanswered,
@@citzOr will a mere boaster be in the right?
<p></p>
</br>3 Will your empty talk itself put men to silence,
@@citzAnd will you keep deriding without having anyone rebuke [you]?
<p></p>
</br>4 Also, you say, ‘My instruction is pure,
@@citzAnd I have proved really clean in your eyes.’
<p></p>
</br>5 Yet O if only God himself would speak
@@citzAnd open his lips with you!
<p></p>
</br>6 Then he would tell you the secrets of wisdom,
@@citzFor the things of practical wisdom are manifold.
@@citzAlso, you would know that God allows some of your error to be forgotten for you.
<p></p>
</br>7 Can you find out the deep things of God,
@@citzOr can you find out to the very limit of the Almighty?
<p></p>
</br>8 It is higher than heaven. What can you accomplish?
@@citzIt is deeper than She´ol. What can you know?
<p></p>
</br>9 It is longer than the earth in measure,
@@citzAnd broader than the sea.
<p></p>
</br>10 If he moves on and hands [someone] over
@@citzAnd calls a court, then who can resist him?
<p></p>
</br>11 For he himself well knows men who are untrue.
@@citzWhen he sees what is hurtful, will he not also show himself attentive?
<p></p>
</br>12 Even a hollow-minded man himself will get good motive
@@citzAs soon as an asinine zebra be born a man.
<p></p>
</br>13 If you yourself will really prepare your heart
@@citzAnd actually spread out your palms to him,
<p></p>
</br>14 If what is hurtful is in your hand, put it far away,
@@citzAnd let no unrighteousness dwell in your tents.
<p></p>
</br>15 For then you will raise your face without defect
@@citzAnd you will certainly become established, and you will not fear.
<p></p>
</br>16 For you—you will forget trouble itself;
@@citzAs waters that have passed along you will remember [it].
<p></p>
</br>17 And brighter than midday will [your] life’s duration arise;
@@citzDarkness will become like the morning itself.
<p></p>
</br>18 And you will be bound to trust because there exists hope;
@@citzAnd you will certainly look carefully around—in security you will lie down.
<p></p>
</br>19 And you will indeed stretch yourself out, with no one to make [you] tremble.
@@citzAnd many people will certainly put you in a gentle mood;
<p></p>
</br>20 And the very eyes of the wicked will fail;
@@citzAnd a place for flight will certainly perish from them,
@@citzAnd their hope will be an expiring of the soul.”
