<p></p>
</br>1 And Job proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “For a fact YOU men are the people,
@@citzAnd with YOU wisdom will die out!
<p></p>
</br>3 I too have a heart as well as YOU.
@@citzI am not inferior to YOU,
@@citzAnd with whom are there not things like these?
<p></p>
</br>4 [One who is] a laughingstock to his fellowman I become,
@@citzOne calling to God that he should answer him.
@@citzA laughingstock is the righteous, unblamable one.
<p></p>
</br>5 In thought, the carefree one has contempt for extinction itself;
@@citzIt is made ready for those of wobbling feet.
<p></p>
</br>6 The tents of the despoilers are unworried,
@@citzAnd the ones enraging God have the safety
@@citzBelonging to one who has brought a god in his hand.
<p></p>
</br>7 However, ask, please, the domestic animals, and they will instruct you;
@@citzAlso the winged creatures of the heavens, and they will tell you.
<p></p>
</br>8 Or show your concern to the earth, and it will instruct you;
@@citzAnd the fishes of the sea will declare it to you.
<p></p>
</br>9 Who among all these does not well know
@@citzThat the hand of Jehovah itself has done this,
<p></p>
</br>10 In whose hand is the soul of everyone alive
@@citzAnd the spirit of all flesh of man?
<p></p>
</br>11 Does not the ear itself test out words
@@citzAs the palate tastes food?
<p></p>
</br>12 Is there not wisdom among the aged
@@citzAnd understanding [in] length of days?
<p></p>
</br>13 With him there are wisdom and mightiness;
@@citzHe has counsel and understanding.
<p></p>
</br>14 Look! He tears down, that there may be no building up;
@@citzHe makes it shut to man, that it may not be opened up.
<p></p>
</br>15 Look! He puts a restraint upon the waters and they dry up;
@@citzAnd he sends them, and they change the earth.
<p></p>
</br>16 With him there are strength and practical wisdom;
@@citzTo him belong the one making a mistake and the one leading astray;
<p></p>
</br>17 He is making counselors go barefoot,
@@citzAnd he makes judges themselves go crazy.
<p></p>
</br>18 The bonds of kings he actually loosens,
@@citzAnd he binds a belt upon their hips.
<p></p>
</br>19 He is making priests walk barefoot,
@@citzAnd permanently seated ones he subverts;
<p></p>
</br>20 He is removing speech from the faithful ones,
@@citzAnd the sensibleness of old men he takes away;
<p></p>
</br>21 He is pouring out contempt upon nobles,
@@citzAnd the girdle of powerful ones he actually weakens;
<p></p>
</br>22 He is uncovering deep things from the darkness,
@@citzAnd he brings forth to the light deep shadow;
<p></p>
</br>23 Making the nations grow great, that he may destroy them;
@@citzSpreading out the nations, that he may lead them away;
<p></p>
</br>24 Taking away the heart of the head ones of the people of the land,
@@citzThat he may make them wander about in an empty place, where there is no way.
<p></p>
</br>25 They grope in darkness, where there is no light,
@@citzThat he may make them wander about like a drunken man.
