<p></p>
</br>1 “Man, born of woman,
@@citzIs short-lived and glutted with agitation.
<p></p>
</br>2 Like a blossom he has come forth and is cut off,
@@citzAnd he runs away like the shadow and does not keep existing.
<p></p>
</br>3 Yes, upon this one you have opened your eye,
@@citzAnd me you bring into judgment with you.
<p></p>
</br>4 Who can produce someone clean out of someone unclean?
@@citzThere is not one.
<p></p>
</br>5 If his days are decided,
@@citzThe number of his months is with you;
@@citzA decree for him you have made that he may not go beyond.
<p></p>
</br>6 Turn your gaze from upon him that he may have rest,
@@citzUntil he finds pleasure as a hired laborer does in his day.
<p></p>
</br>7 For there exists hope for even a tree.
@@citzIf it gets cut down, it will even sprout again,
@@citzAnd its own twig will not cease to be.
<p></p>
</br>8 If its root grows old in the earth
@@citzAnd in the dust its stump dies,
<p></p>
</br>9 At the scent of water it will sprout
@@citzAnd it will certainly produce a bough like a new plant.
<p></p>
</br>10 But an able-bodied man dies and lies vanquished;
@@citzAnd an earthling man expires, and where is he?
<p></p>
</br>11 Waters do disappear from a sea,
@@citzAnd a river itself drains off and dries up.
<p></p>
</br>12 Man also has to lie down and does not get up.
@@citzUntil heaven is no more they will not wake up,
@@citzNor will they be aroused from their sleep.
<p></p>
</br>13 O that in She´ol you would conceal me,
@@citzThat you would keep me secret until your anger turns back,
@@citzThat you would set a time limit for me and remember me!
<p></p>
</br>14 If an able-bodied man dies can he live again?
@@citzAll the days of my compulsory service I shall wait,
@@citzUntil my relief comes.
<p></p>
</br>15 You will call, and I myself shall answer you.
@@citzFor the work of your hands you will have a yearning.
<p></p>
</br>16 For now you keep counting my very steps;
@@citzYou watch for nothing but my sin.
<p></p>
</br>17 Sealed up in a bag is my revolt,
@@citzAnd you apply glue over my error.
<p></p>
</br>18 However, a mountain itself, falling, will fade away,
@@citzAnd even a rock will be moved away from its place.
<p></p>
</br>19 Water certainly rubs away even stones;
@@citzIts outpouring washes off earth’s dust.
@@citzSo you have destroyed the very hope of mortal man.
<p></p>
</br>20 You overpower him forever so that he goes away;
@@citzYou are disfiguring his face so that you send him away.
<p></p>
</br>21 His sons get honored, but he does not know [it];
@@citzAnd they become insignificant, but he does not consider them.
<p></p>
</br>22 Only his own flesh while upon him will keep aching,
@@citzAnd his own soul while within him will keep mourning.”
