<p></p>
</br>1 And Job proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “I have heard many things like these.
@@citzAll of YOU are troublesome comforters!
<p></p>
</br>3 Is there an end to windy words?
@@citzOr what galls you, that you answer?
<p></p>
</br>4 I myself also could well speak as YOU men do.
@@citzIf only YOUR souls existed where my soul is,
@@citpWould I be brilliant in words against YOU,
@@citzAnd would I wag my head against YOU?
<p></p>
</br>5 I would strengthen YOU with the words of my mouth,
@@citzAnd the consolation of my own lips would hold back—.
<p></p>
</br>6 If I do speak, my own pain is not held back,
@@citzAnd if I do cease doing so, what goes away from me?
<p></p>
</br>7 Only now he has made me weary;
@@citzHe has made all those assembling with me desolate.
<p></p>
</br>8 You also seize me. It has become a witness,
@@citzSo that my leanness rises up against me. In my face it testifies.
<p></p>
</br>9 His very anger has torn [me] to pieces, and he harbors animosity against me.
@@citzHe actually grinds his teeth against me.
@@citzMy adversary himself sharpens his eyes against me.
<p></p>
</br>10 They have opened their mouth wide against me,
@@citzWith reproach they have struck my cheeks,
@@citzIn large number they mass themselves against me.
<p></p>
</br>11 God hands me over to young boys,
@@citzAnd into the hands of wicked ones he throws me headlong.
<p></p>
</br>12 I had come to be at ease, but he proceeded to shake me up;
@@citzAnd he grabbed me by the back of the neck and proceeded to smash me,
@@citzAnd he sets me up as a target for himself.
<p></p>
</br>13 His archers encircle me;
@@citzHe splits open my kidneys and feels no compassion;
@@citzHe pours out my gallbladder to the very earth.
<p></p>
</br>14 He keeps breaking through me with breach after breach;
@@citzHe runs at me like a mighty one.
<p></p>
</br>15 Sackcloth I have sewed together over my skin,
@@citzAnd I have thrust my horn in the very dust.
<p></p>
</br>16 My face itself has become reddened from weeping,
@@citzAnd upon my eyelids there is deep shadow,
<p></p>
</br>17 Although there is no violence upon my palms,
@@citzAnd my prayer is pure.
<p></p>
</br>18 O earth, do not cover my blood!
@@citzAnd let there prove to be no place for my outcry!
<p></p>
</br>19 Also now, look! in the heavens is one testifying about me,
@@citzAnd my witness is in the heights.
<p></p>
</br>20 My companions are spokesmen against me;
@@citzTo God my eye has looked sleeplessly.
<p></p>
</br>21 And the decision is to be made between an able-bodied man and God,
@@citzThe same as between a son of man and his fellow.
<p></p>
</br>22 For just a few years are to come,
@@citzAnd by the path by which I shall not return I shall go away.
@@libJob 
</br>17 :
</br>1 -
</br>16 
<p></p>
</br>1 “My very spirit has been broken, my own days have been extinguished;
@@citzThe graveyard is for me.
<p></p>
</br>2 Certainly there is mockery at me,
@@citzAnd amid their rebellious behavior my eye lodges.
<p></p>
</br>3 Please, do put my security with yourself.
@@citzWho else is there that will shake hands with me in pledge?
<p></p>
</br>4 For their heart you have closed to discretion.
@@citzThat is why you do not exalt them.
<p></p>
</br>5 He may tell companions to take their shares,
@@citzBut the very eyes of his sons will fail.
<p></p>
</br>6 And he has set me forth as a proverbial saying of peoples,
@@citzSo that I become someone into whose face to spit.
<p></p>
</br>7 And from vexation my eye grows dimmer
@@citzAnd my members are all of them like the shadow.
<p></p>
</br>8 Upright people stare in amazement at this,
@@citzAnd even the innocent one gets excited over the apostate.
<p></p>
</br>9 The righteous one keeps holding fast to his way,
@@citzAnd the one with clean hands keeps increasing in strength.
<p></p>
</br>10 However, YOU men may all of YOU resume. So come on, please,
@@citzAs I do not find anyone wise among YOU.
<p></p>
</br>11 My own days have passed along, my own plans have been torn apart,
@@citzThe wishes of my heart.
<p></p>
</br>12 Night they keep putting for day:
@@citz‘Light is near on account of darkness.’
<p></p>
</br>13 If I keep waiting, She´ol is my house;
@@citzIn the darkness I shall have to spread out my lounge.
<p></p>
</br>14 To the pit I shall have to call out, ‘You are my father!’
@@citzTo the maggot, ‘My mother and my sister!’
<p></p>
</br>15 So where, then, is my hope?
@@citzAnd my hope—who is it that beholds it?
<p></p>
</br>16 To the bars of She´ol they will go down,
@@citzWhen we, all together, must descend to the very dust.”
@@libJob 
</br>18 :
