<p></p>
</br>1 And Bil´dad the Shu´hite proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “How long will YOU people be at putting an end to words?
@@citzYOU should understand, that afterward we may speak.
<p></p>
</br>3 Why should we be reckoned as beasts
@@citz[And] be regarded as unclean in YOUR eyes?
<p></p>
</br>4 He is tearing his soul to pieces in his anger.
@@citzFor your sake will the earth be abandoned,
@@citzOr a rock move away from its place?
<p></p>
</br>5 The light also of wicked ones will be extinguished
@@citzAnd the spark of his fire will not shine.
<p></p>
</br>6 A light itself will certainly grow dark in his tent,
@@citzAnd in it his own lamp will be extinguished.
<p></p>
</br>7 His steps of vigor will become cramped.
@@citzEven his counsel will cast him off.
<p></p>
</br>8 For he will indeed be let go into a net by his feet,
@@citzAnd onto a network he will walk.
<p></p>
</br>9 A trap will seize [him] by the heel;
@@citzA snare keeps hold upon him.
<p></p>
</br>10 A cord for him is hidden on the earth,
@@citzAnd a catching device for him on [his] pathway.
<p></p>
</br>11 Round about, sudden terrors certainly make him start up in fright,
@@citzAnd indeed chase him at his feet.
<p></p>
</br>12 His vigor becomes famished,
@@citzAnd disaster stands ready to make him limp.
<p></p>
</br>13 It will eat the pieces of his skin;
@@citzThe firstborn of death will eat his limbs.
<p></p>
</br>14 His confidence will be torn away from his own tent
@@citzAnd it will march him to the king of terrors.
<p></p>
</br>15 There will reside in his tent something that is not his;
@@citzSulphur will be strewed upon his own abiding place.
<p></p>
</br>16 Underneath will his very roots dry up,
@@citzAnd, up above, his bough will wither.
<p></p>
</br>17 The very mentioning of him will certainly perish from the earth,
@@citzAnd he will have no name out in the street.
<p></p>
</br>18 They will push him out of the light into the darkness,
@@citzAnd from the productive land they will chase him away.
<p></p>
</br>19 He will have no posterity and no progeny among his people,
@@citzAnd there will be no survivor in his place of alien residence.
<p></p>
</br>20 At his day the people in the West will indeed stare in amazement,
@@citzAnd a shudder will certainly seize even the people in the East.
<p></p>
</br>21 Only these are the tabernacles of a wrongdoer,
@@citzAnd this is the place of one that has not known God.”
@@libJob 
</br>19 :
</br>1 -
</br>29 
<p></p>
</br>1 And Job proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “How long will YOU men keep irritating my soul
@@citzAnd keep crushing me with words?
<p></p>
</br>3 These ten times YOU proceeded to rebuke me;
@@citzYOU are not ashamed [that] YOU deal so hard with me.
<p></p>
</br>4 And, granted that I have made a mistake,
@@citzIt is with me that my mistake will lodge.
<p></p>
</br>5 If for a fact against me YOU men do put on great airs,
@@citzAnd YOU show my reproach to be proper against me,
<p></p>
</br>6 KNOW, then, that God himself has misled me,
@@citzAnd his hunting net he has closed in upon me.
<p></p>
</br>7 Look! I keep crying out, ‘Violence!’ but I get no answer;
@@citzI keep crying for help, but there is no justice.
<p></p>
</br>8 My very path he has blocked with a stone wall, and I cannot pass over;
@@citzAnd upon my roadways he puts darkness itself.
<p></p>
</br>9 My own glory he has stripped from me,
@@citzAnd he takes away the crown of my head.
<p></p>
</br>10 He pulls me down on all sides, and I go away;
@@citzAnd he pulls my hope out just like a tree.
<p></p>
</br>11 His anger also grows hot against me,
@@citzAnd he keeps reckoning me as an adversary of his.
<p></p>
</br>12 Unitedly his troops come and cast up their way against me,
@@citzAnd they camp round about my tent.
<p></p>
</br>13 My own brothers he has put far away from me,
@@citzAnd the very ones knowing me have even turned aside from me.
<p></p>
</br>14 My intimate acquaintances have ceased to be,
@@citzAnd those known by me have themselves forgotten me,
<p></p>
</br>15 Those residing as aliens in my house; and my slave girls themselves reckon me as a stranger;
@@citzA real foreigner I have become in their eyes.
<p></p>
</br>16 To my servant I have called, but he does not answer.
@@citzWith my own mouth I keep imploring him for compassion.
<p></p>
</br>17 My breath itself has become loathsome to my wife,
@@citzAnd I have become foul-smelling to the sons of my [mother’s] belly.
<p></p>
</br>18 Also young boys themselves have rejected me;
@@citzLet me but rise up, and they begin to speak against me.
<p></p>
</br>19 All the men of my intimate group detest me,
@@citzAnd those whom I loved have turned against me.
<p></p>
</br>20 To my skin and to my flesh my bones actually cleave,
@@citzAnd I escape with the skin of my teeth.
<p></p>
</br>21 Show me some favor, show me some favor, O YOU my companions,
@@citzFor God’s own hand has touched me.
<p></p>
</br>22 Why do YOU men keep persecuting me as God does,
@@citzAnd not become satisfied with my very flesh?
<p></p>
</br>23 O that now my words were written down!
@@citzO that in a book they were even inscribed!
<p></p>
</br>24 With an iron stylus and [with] lead,
@@citzForever in the rock O that they were hewn!
<p></p>
</br>25 And I myself well know that my redeemer is alive,
@@citzAnd that, coming after [me], he will rise up over [the] dust.
<p></p>
</br>26 And after my skin, [which] they have skinned off,—this!
@@citzYet reduced in my flesh I shall behold God,
<p></p>
</br>27 Whom even I shall behold for myself,
@@citzAnd [whom] my very eyes will certainly see, but not some stranger.
@@citzMy kidneys have failed deep within me.
<p></p>
</br>28 For YOU men say, ‘Why do we keep persecuting him?’
@@citzWhen the very root of [the] matter is found in me.
<p></p>
</br>29 Be frightened for yourselves because of a sword,
@@citzFor the sword means a raging against errors,
@@citzIn order that YOU men may know there is a judge.”
