<p></p>
</br>1 And Zo´phar the Na´a·ma·thite proceeded to reply and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “Therefore do my own disquieting thoughts themselves answer me,
@@citzEven on account of my inward excitement.
<p></p>
</br>3 An insulting exhortation to me I hear;
@@citzAnd a spirit without the understanding that I have replies to me.
<p></p>
</br>4 Have you at all times known this very thing,
@@citzSince man was put upon the earth,
<p></p>
</br>5 That the joyful cry of wicked people is short
@@citzAnd the rejoicing of an apostate is for a moment?
<p></p>
</br>6 Although his excellency ascends to heaven itself
@@citzAnd his very head reaches to the clouds,
<p></p>
</br>7 Like his manure cakes he perishes forever;
@@citzThe very ones seeing him will say, ‘Where is he?’
<p></p>
</br>8 Like a dream he will fly off, and they will not find him;
@@citzAnd he will be chased away like a vision of the night.
<p></p>
</br>9 The eye that has caught sight of him will not do so again,
@@citzAnd no more will his place behold him.
<p></p>
</br>10 His own sons will seek the favor of lowly people,
@@citzAnd his own hands will give back his valuable things.
<p></p>
</br>11 His own bones have been full of his youthful vigor,
@@citzBut with him it will lie down in mere dust.
<p></p>
</br>12 If what is bad tastes sweet in his mouth,
@@citzIf he causes it to melt away under his tongue,
<p></p>
</br>13 If he has compassion upon it and does not leave it,
@@citzAnd if he keeps holding it back in the midst of his palate,
<p></p>
</br>14 His food itself will certainly be changed in his own intestines;
@@citzIt will be the gall of cobras within him.
<p></p>
</br>15 Wealth he has swallowed down, but he will vomit it up;
@@citzGod will drive it out from his very belly.
<p></p>
</br>16 The venom of cobras he will suck;
@@citzThe tongue of a viper will kill him.
<p></p>
</br>17 He will never see the watercourses,
@@citzTorrential streams of honey and butter.
<p></p>
</br>18 He will be giving back [his] acquired property and will not swallow [it] down;
@@citzLike wealth from his trade, but which he will not enjoy.
<p></p>
</br>19 For he has crushed to pieces, he has left lowly ones;
@@citzHe has snatched away a house itself that he did not proceed to build.
<p></p>
</br>20 For he will certainly know no ease in his belly;
@@citzBy means of his desirable things he will not escape.
<p></p>
</br>21 There is nothing left over for him to devour;
@@citzThat is why his well-being will not endure.
<p></p>
</br>22 While his plenty is at its peak he will be feeling anxious;
@@citzAll the power of misfortune itself will come against him.
<p></p>
</br>23 Let it occur that, to fill his belly,
@@citzHe will send his burning anger upon him
@@citzAnd will rain [it] upon him, into his bowels.
<p></p>
</br>24 He will run away from armor of iron;
@@citzA bow of copper will cut him up.
<p></p>
</br>25 A missile itself will even go out through his back,
@@citzAnd a glittering weapon out through his gall;
@@citzFrightful objects will go against him.
<p></p>
</br>26 All darkness will be reserved for his treasured things;
@@citzA fire that no one fanned will eat him up;
@@citzIt will go badly with a survivor in his tent.
<p></p>
</br>27 Heaven will uncover his error,
@@citzAnd earth will be in revolt against him.
<p></p>
</br>28 A heavy shower will roll his house away;
@@citzThere will be things poured forth on the day of his anger.
<p></p>
</br>29 This is the share of the wicked man from God,
@@citzEven his stated inheritance from God.”
@@libJob 
