<p></p>
</br>1 And Job proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “Listen, YOU men, attentively to my word,
@@citzAnd let this become YOUR consolation.
<p></p>
</br>3 Put up with me, and I myself shall speak;
@@citzAnd after my speaking you may [each] deride.
<p></p>
</br>4 As for me, is my concern [expressed] to man?
@@citzOr why is it that my spirit does not get impatient?
<p></p>
</br>5 Turn YOUR faces to me and stare in amazement,
@@citzAnd put [YOUR] hand upon [YOUR] mouth.
<p></p>
</br>6 And if I have remembered, I have also become disturbed,
@@citzAnd shuddering has taken hold of my flesh.
<p></p>
</br>7 Why is it that the wicked themselves keep living,
@@citzHave grown old, also have become superior in wealth?
<p></p>
</br>8 Their offspring are firmly established with them in their sight,
@@citzAnd their descendants before their eyes.
<p></p>
</br>9 Their houses are peace itself, free from dread,
@@citzAnd the rod of God is not upon them.
<p></p>
</br>10 His own bull actually impregnates, and it does not waste semen;
@@citzHis cow brings forth and suffers no abortion.
<p></p>
</br>11 They keep sending out their young boys just like a flock,
@@citzAnd their own male children go skipping about.
<p></p>
</br>12 They continue raising [their voice] with the tambourine and harp,
@@citzAnd keep rejoicing at the sound of the pipe.
<p></p>
</br>13 They spend their days in good times,
@@citzAnd in a moment down to She´ol they descend.
<p></p>
</br>14 And they say to the [true] God, ‘Turn away from us!
@@citzAnd in the knowledge of your ways we have found no delight.
<p></p>
</br>15 What does the Almighty amount to, that we should serve him,
@@citzAnd how do we benefit ourselves in that we have come in touch with him?’
<p></p>
</br>16 Look! Their well-being is not in their own power.
@@citzThe very counsel of wicked ones has kept far from me.
<p></p>
</br>17 How many times is the lamp of the wicked ones extinguished,
@@citzAnd [how many times] does their disaster come upon them?
@@citz[How many times] in his anger does he apportion destruction?
<p></p>
</br>18 Do they become like straw before a wind,
@@citzAnd like chaff that a storm wind has stolen away?
<p></p>
</br>19 God himself will store up one’s hurtfulness for one’s own sons;
@@citzHe will reward him that he may know [it].
<p></p>
</br>20 His eyes will see his decay,
@@citzAnd from the rage of the Almighty he will drink.
<p></p>
</br>21 For what will his delight be in his house after him,
@@citzWhen the number of his months will really be cut in two?
<p></p>
</br>22 Will he teach knowledge even to God,
@@citzWhen that One himself judges high ones?
<p></p>
</br>23 This very one will die during his full self-sufficiency,
@@citzWhen he is altogether carefree and at ease;
<p></p>
</br>24 [When] his own thighs have become full of fat
@@citzAnd the very marrow of his bones is being kept moist.
<p></p>
</br>25 And this other one will die with a bitter soul
@@citzWhen he has not eaten of good things.
<p></p>
</br>26 Together in the dust they will lie down
@@citzAnd maggots themselves will form a cover over them.
<p></p>
</br>27 Look! I well know the thoughts of YOU men
@@citzAnd the schemes with which YOU would act violently against me.
<p></p>
</br>28 For YOU say, ‘Where is the house of the noble one,
@@citzAnd where is the tent, the tabernacles of wicked ones?’
<p></p>
</br>29 Have YOU not asked those traveling over the roads?
@@citzAnd do YOU not carefully inspect their very signs,
<p></p>
</br>30 That at the day of disaster an evil one is spared,
@@citzAt the day of fury he is delivered?
<p></p>
</br>31 Who will tell him of his way to his very face?
@@citzAnd for what he himself has done who will reward him?
<p></p>
</br>32 As for him, to the graveyard he will be brought,
@@citzAnd over a tomb a vigil will be kept.
<p></p>
</br>33 To him the clods of earth of a torrent valley will certainly become sweet,
@@citzAnd after him he will drag all mankind,
@@citzAnd those before him were without number.
<p></p>
</br>34 So how vainly YOU men try to comfort me,
@@citzAnd YOUR very replies do remain as unfaithfulness!”
