@@citzAnd will there be no end to your errors?
<p></p>
</br>6 For you seize a pledge from your brothers without cause,
@@citzAnd you strip off even the garments of naked people.
<p></p>
</br>7 You do not give the tired one a drink of water,
@@citzAnd from the hungry one you hold back bread.
<p></p>
</br>8 As for a man of strength, the land is his,
@@citzAnd one who is treated with partiality himself dwells in it.
<p></p>
</br>9 Widows you have sent away empty-handed,
@@citzAnd the arms of fatherless boys are crushed.
<p></p>
</br>10 That is why bird traps are all around you,
@@citzAnd sudden dread disturbs you;
<p></p>
</br>11 Or darkness, [so that] you cannot see,
@@citzAnd a heaving mass of water itself covers you.
<p></p>
