@@citzAnd put his sayings in your heart.
<p></p>
</br>23 If you return to the Almighty, you will be built up;
@@citz[If] you will keep unrighteousness far from your tent,
<p></p>
</br>24 And [if] there is a placing of precious ore in the dust
@@citzAnd gold of O´phir in the rock of torrent valleys,
<p></p>
</br>25 The Almighty also will indeed become your precious ores,
@@citzAnd silver, the choicest, to you.
<p></p>
</br>26 For then in the Almighty you will find your exquisite delight,
@@citzAnd you will raise your face to God himself.
<p></p>
</br>27 You will make entreaty to him, and he will hear you;
@@citzAnd your vows you will pay.
<p></p>
</br>28 And you will decide on something, and it will stand for you;
@@citzAnd upon your ways light will certainly shine.
<p></p>
</br>29 For there must be a humiliation when you speak arrogantly;
@@citzBut one with downcast eyes he will save.
<p></p>
</br>30 He will rescue an innocent man,
@@citzAnd you will certainly be rescued for the cleanness of your hands.”
@@libJob 
</br>23 :
</br>1 -
</br>17 
<p></p>
</br>1 And Job proceeded to answer and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “Even today my state of concern is rebelliousness;
@@citzMy own hand is heavy on account of my sighing.
<p></p>
</br>3 O that I really knew where I might find him!
@@citzI would come clear to his fixed place.
<p></p>
</br>4 I would present before him a case of justice,
@@citzAnd my mouth I would fill with counterarguments;
<p></p>
</br>5 I would know the words with which he answers me,
@@citzAnd I would consider what he says to me.
<p></p>
</br>6 Would he with an abundance of power contend with me?
@@citzO no! Surely he himself would pay heed to me.
<p></p>
</br>7 There the upright one himself will certainly set matters straight with him,
@@citzAnd I would go safe forever from my judge.
<p></p>
</br>8 Look! To the east I go, and he is not there;
@@citzAnd back again, and I cannot discern him;
<p></p>
</br>9 To the left where he is working, but I cannot behold [him];
@@citzHe turns aside to the right, but I do not see [him].
<p></p>
</br>10 For he well knows the way I take.
@@citz[After] he has tested me out, I shall come forth as gold itself.
<p></p>
</br>11 Of his steps my foot has laid hold;
@@citzHis way I have kept, and I do not deviate.
<p></p>
</br>12 [From] the commandment of his lips I do not move away.
@@citzI have treasured up the sayings of his mouth more than what is prescribed for me.
<p></p>
</br>13 And he is in one [mind], and who can resist him?
@@citzAnd his own soul has a desire, and he will do [it].
<p></p>
</br>14 For he will carry out completely what is prescribed for me,
@@citzAnd things like these are many with him.
<p></p>
</br>15 That is why I feel disturbed because of him;
@@citzI show myself attentive and am in dread of him.
<p></p>
</br>16 Even God himself has made my heart timid,
@@citzAnd the Almighty himself has disturbed me.
<p></p>
</br>17 For I have not been put to silence because of darkness,
@@citzNor because gloom has covered my own face.
@@libJob 
</br>24 :
</br>1 -
