<p></p>
</br>1 “Why is it that times have not been stored up by the Almighty himself,
@@citzAnd the very ones knowing him have not beheld his days?
<p></p>
</br>2 There are those who move back boundary marks;
@@citzA drove they have snatched away, that they may shepherd [it].
<p></p>
</br>3 They drive off even the male ass of fatherless boys;
@@citzThey seize the widow’s bull as a pledge.
<p></p>
</br>4 They turn aside the poor ones from the way;
@@citzAt the same time the afflicted of the earth have kept themselves hidden.
<p></p>
</br>5 Look! [As] zebras in the wilderness
@@citzThey have gone forth in their activity, looking for food.
@@citzThe desert plain [gives] to each one bread for the boys.
<p></p>
</br>6 In the field its fodder they harvest,
@@citzAnd the vineyard of the wicked one they hastily despoil.
<p></p>
</br>7 Naked, they pass the night without a garment,
@@citzAnd without any covering in the cold.
<p></p>
</br>8 From the rainstorm of the mountains they get drenched,
@@citzAnd because there is no shelter they have to hug a rock.
<p></p>
</br>9 They snatch away a fatherless boy even from the breast,
@@citzAnd what is on the afflicted one they take as a pledge.
<p></p>
</br>10 Naked, they have to go about without a garment,
@@citzAnd, hungry, they have to carry the reaped ears.
<p></p>
</br>11 Between the terrace walls they pass the noontime;
@@citzWinepresses they have to tread, and yet they go thirsty.
<p></p>
</br>12 From out of the city the dying keep groaning,
@@citzAnd the soul of deadly wounded ones cries for help;
@@citzAnd God himself considers [it] not as anything improper.
<p></p>
</br>13 As for them, they proved to be among the rebels against light;
@@citzThey did not recognize its ways,
@@citzAnd they did not dwell in its roadways.
<p></p>
</br>14 At daylight the murderer gets up,
@@citzHe proceeds to slay the afflicted and the poor one;
@@citzAnd during the night he becomes a regular thief.
<p></p>
</br>15 As for the eye of the adulterer, it has watched for evening darkness,
@@citzSaying, ‘No eye will behold me!’
@@citzAnd over his face he puts a covering.
<p></p>
</br>16 In the darkness he has dug into houses;
@@citzBy day they must keep themselves locked in.
@@citzThey have not known daylight.
<p></p>
</br>17 For morning is the same as deep shadow for them,
@@citzFor they recognize what the sudden terrors of deep shadow are.
<p></p>
</br>18 He is swift on the surface of the waters.
@@citzTheir tract of land will be cursed in the earth.
@@citzHe will not turn toward the way of the vineyards.
<p></p>
</br>19 The drought, also the heat, snatch away the snow waters;
@@citzSo does She´ol those who have sinned!
<p></p>
</br>20 The womb will forget him, the maggot will sweetly suck him,
@@citzHe will be remembered no more.
@@citzAnd unrighteousness will be broken just like a tree.
<p></p>
</br>21 He is having dealings with a barren woman who does not bear,
@@citzAnd with a widow, to whom he does no good.
<p></p>
</br>22 And he will certainly draw away strong people by his power;
@@citzHe will rise up and not be sure of his life.
<p></p>
</br>23 He will grant him to become confident that he may support himself;
@@citzAnd his eyes will be upon their ways.
<p></p>
</br>24 They have become high up a little while, then they are no more,
@@citzAnd they have been brought low; like everyone else they are plucked off,
@@citzAnd like the head of an ear of grain they are cut off.
<p></p>
</br>25 So really now, who will make me out a liar
@@citzOr reduce my word to nothing?”
