</br>2 “As God lives, who has taken away my judgment,
@@citzAnd as the Almighty [lives], who has made my soul bitter,
<p></p>
</br>3 While my breath is yet whole within me,
@@citzAnd the spirit of God is in my nostrils,
<p></p>
</br>4 My lips will speak no unrighteousness
@@citzAnd my own tongue will mutter no deceit!
<p></p>
</br>5 It is unthinkable on my part that I should declare YOU men righteous!
@@citzUntil I expire I shall not take away my integrity from myself!
<p></p>
</br>6 On my justness I have laid hold, and I shall not let it go;
@@citzMy heart will not taunt [me] for any of my days.
<p></p>
</br>7 Let my enemy become in every way a wicked man,
@@citzAnd the one revolting against me really a wrongdoer.
<p></p>
</br>8 For what is the hope of an apostate in case he cuts [him] off,
@@citzIn case God carries off his soul from him?
<p></p>
</br>9 Will God hear an outcry of his
@@citzIn case distress comes upon him?
<p></p>
</br>10 Or in the Almighty will he find exquisite delight?
@@citzWill he call to God at all times?
<p></p>
</br>11 I shall instruct YOU men by the hand of God;
@@citzThat which is with the Almighty I shall not hide.
<p></p>
</br>12 Look! YOU yourselves have all of YOU seen visions;
@@citzSo why is it that YOU show yourselves utterly vain?
<p></p>
</br>13 This is the share of the wicked man from God;
@@citzAnd the inheritance of the tyrants they will receive from the Almighty himself.
<p></p>
</br>14 If his sons become many, it is for a sword;
@@citzAnd his descendants themselves will not have enough food.
<p></p>
</br>15 His own survivors will be buried during a deadly plague,
@@citzAnd their own widows will not weep.
<p></p>
</br>16 If he should pile up silver like dust itself,
@@citzAnd he should prepare attire just as if clay,
<p></p>
</br>17 He would prepare, but the righteous would be the one to clothe himself,
@@citzAnd in the silver the innocent would be the one to have a share.
<p></p>
</br>18 He has built his house like a mere moth,
@@citzAnd like a booth that a watchman has made.
<p></p>
</br>19 Rich he will lie down, but nothing will be gathered;
@@citzHis eyes he has opened, but there will be nothing.
<p></p>
</br>20 Like waters sudden terrors will overtake him;
@@citzAt night a storm wind will certainly steal him away.
<p></p>
</br>21 An east wind will carry him off and he will go away,
@@citzAnd it will whirl him away from his place.
<p></p>
</br>22 And it will hurl itself at him and have no compassion;
@@citzFrom its power he will without fail try to run away.
<p></p>
</br>23 One will clap his hands at him
@@citzAnd will whistle at him from his place.
