<p></p>
</br>1 “Indeed, for silver there exists a place to find it
@@citzAnd a place for gold that they refine;
<p></p>
</br>2 Iron itself is taken from the very dust
@@citzAnd [from] stone copper is being poured out.
<p></p>
</br>3 An end to the darkness he has set;
@@citzAnd to every limit he is searching out
@@citzStone in the gloom and deep shadow.
<p></p>
</br>4 He has sunk a shaft far from where [people] reside as aliens,
@@citzPlaces forgotten far from the foot;
@@citzSome of mortal men have swung down, they have dangled.
<p></p>
</br>5 As for the earth, out of it food goes forth;
@@citzBut underneath it, it has been upturned as if by fire.
<p></p>
</br>6 Its stones are the place of the sapphire,
@@citzAnd it has gold dust.
<p></p>
</br>7 A pathway—no bird of prey has known it,
@@citzNor has the eye of a black kite caught sight of it.
<p></p>
</br>8 The majestic wild beasts have not trodden it down solid;
@@citzThe young lion has not paced over it.
<p></p>
</br>9 Upon the flint he has thrust out his hand;
@@citzHe has overthrown mountains from [their] root;
<p></p>
</br>10 Into the rocks he has channeled water-filled galleries,
@@citzAnd all precious things his eye has seen.
<p></p>
</br>11 The places from which rivers trickled he has dammed up,
@@citzAnd the concealed thing he brings forth to the light.
<p></p>
</br>12 But wisdom—where can it be found,
@@citzAnd where, now, is the place of understanding?
<p></p>
</br>13 Mortal man has not come to know its valuation,
@@citzAnd it is not found in the land of those living.
<p></p>
</br>14 The watery deep itself has said,
@@citz‘It is not in me!’
@@citzThe sea too has said, ‘It is not with me!’
<p></p>
</br>15 Pure gold cannot be given in exchange for it,
@@citzAnd silver cannot be weighed out as its price.
<p></p>
</br>16 It cannot be paid for with gold of O´phir,
@@citzWith the rare onyx stone and the sapphire.
<p></p>
</br>17 Gold and glass cannot be compared to it,
@@citzNor is any vessel of refined gold an exchange for it.
<p></p>
</br>18 Coral and rock crystal themselves will not be mentioned,
@@citzBut a bagful of wisdom is worth more than [one full of] pearls.
<p></p>
</br>19 The topaz of Cush cannot be compared to it;
@@citzIt cannot be paid for even with gold in its purity.
<p></p>
</br>20 But wisdom itself—from where does it come,
@@citzAnd where, now, is the place of understanding?
<p></p>
</br>21 It has been hidden even from the eyes of everyone alive,
@@citzAnd from the flying creatures of the heavens it has been concealed.
<p></p>
</br>22 Destruction and death themselves have said,
@@citz‘With our ears we have heard a report of it.’
<p></p>
</br>23 God is the One who has understood its way,
@@citzAnd he himself has known its place,
<p></p>
</br>24 For he himself looks to the very ends of the earth;
@@citzUnder the whole heavens he sees,
<p></p>
</br>25 To make a weight for the wind,
@@citzWhile he has proportioned the waters themselves by a measure;
<p></p>
</br>26 When he made for the rain a regulation,
@@citzAnd a way for the thunderous storm cloud,
<p></p>
</br>27 Then it was that he saw [wisdom] and proceeded to tell about it;
@@citzHe prepared it and also searched it through.
<p></p>
</br>28 And he went on to say to man,
@@citz‘Look! The fear of Jehovah—that is wisdom,
@@citzAnd to turn away from bad is understanding.’”
