@@citzWhen intimacy with God was at my tent;
<p></p>
</br>5 When the Almighty was yet with me,
@@citz[When] my attendants were all around me!
<p></p>
</br>6 When I washed my steps in butter,
@@citzAnd the rock kept pouring out streams of oil for me;
<p></p>
</br>7 When I went forth to the gate by the town,
@@citzIn the public square I would prepare my seat!
<p></p>
</br>8 The boys saw me and hid themselves,
@@citzAnd even the aged ones rose up, they stood.
<p></p>
</br>9 Princes themselves restrained words,
@@citzAnd the palm they would put upon their mouth.
<p></p>
</br>10 The voice of the leaders themselves was hidden,
@@citzAnd their very tongue cleaved to their palate.
<p></p>
</br>11 For the ear itself listened and proceeded to pronounce me happy,
@@citzAnd the eye itself saw and proceeded to bear witness for me.
<p></p>
</br>12 For I would rescue the afflicted one crying for help,
@@citzAnd the fatherless boy and anyone that had no helper.
<p></p>
</br>13 The blessing of the one about to perish—upon me it would come,
@@citzAnd the heart of the widow I would make glad.
<p></p>
</br>14 With righteousness I clothed myself, and it was clothing me.
@@citzMy justice was like a sleeveless coat—and a turban.
<p></p>
</br>15 Eyes I became to the blind one;
@@citzAnd feet to the lame one I was.
<p></p>
</br>16 I was a real father to the poor ones;
@@citzAnd the legal case of one whom I did not know—I would examine it.
<p></p>
</br>17 And I would break the jawbones of the wrongdoer,
@@citzAnd from his teeth I would tear away the prey.
<p></p>
</br>18 And I used to say, ‘Within my nest I shall expire,
@@citzAnd like the grains of sand I shall multiply [my] days.
<p></p>
</br>19 My root is opened for the waters,
@@citzAnd dew itself will stay overnight upon my bough.
<p></p>
</br>20 My glory is fresh with me,
@@citzAnd my bow in my hand will shoot repeatedly.’
<p></p>
</br>21 To me they listened; and they waited,
@@citzAnd they would keep silent for my counsel.
<p></p>
</br>22 After my word they would not speak again,
@@citzAnd upon them my word would drip.
<p></p>
</br>23 And they waited for me as for the rain,
@@citzAnd their mouth they opened wide for the spring rain.
<p></p>
</br>24 I would smile at them—they would not believe [it]—
@@citzAnd the light of my face they would not cast down.
<p></p>
</br>25 I would choose the way for them, and I was sitting as head;
@@citzAnd I resided as a king among [his] troops,
@@citzAs one who comforts the mourners.
