@@citzAnd the eyes of the widow I would cause to fail,
<p></p>
</br>17 And I used to eat my morsel by myself,
@@citzWhile the fatherless boy did not eat from it
<p></p>
</br>18 (For from my youth he grew up with me as with a father,
@@citzAnd from the belly of my mother I kept leading her);
<p></p>
</br>19 If I used to see anyone perishing from having no garment,
@@citzOr that the poor one had no covering;
<p></p>
</br>20 If his loins did not bless me,
@@citzNor from the shorn wool of my young rams he would warm himself;
<p></p>
</br>21 If I waved my hand to and fro against the fatherless boy,
@@citzWhen I would see [need of] my assistance in the gate,
<p></p>
</br>22 Let my own shoulder blade fall from its shoulder,
@@citzAnd let my own arm be broken from its upper bone.
<p></p>
</br>23 For disaster from God was a dread to me,
@@citzAnd against his dignity I could not hold out.
<p></p>
</br>24 If I have put gold as my confidence,
@@citzOr to gold I have said, ‘You are my trust!’
<p></p>
</br>25 If I used to rejoice because my property was much,
@@citzAnd because my hand had found a lot of things;
<p></p>
</br>26 If I used to see the light when it would flash forth,
@@citzOr the precious moon walking along,
<p></p>
</br>27 And my heart began to be enticed in secrecy
@@citzAnd my hand proceeded to kiss my mouth,
<p></p>
</br>28 That too would be an error for [attention by] the justices,
@@citzFor I should have denied the [true] God above.
<p></p>
</br>29 If I used to rejoice at the extinction of one intensely hating me,
@@citzOr I felt excited because evil had found him—
<p></p>
</br>30 And I did not allow my palate to sin
@@citzBy asking for an oath against his soul.
<p></p>
</br>31 If the men of my tent did not say,
@@citz‘Who can produce anyone that has not been satisfied from food of his?’—
<p></p>
</br>32 Outside no alien resident would spend the night;
@@citzMy doors I kept open to the path.
<p></p>
</br>33 If like an earthling man I covered over my transgressions
@@citzBy hiding my error in my shirt pocket—
<p></p>
</br>34 Because I would suffer a shock at a large crowd,
@@citzOr the contempt itself of families would terrorize me
@@citzAnd I would keep silent, I would not go out of the entrance.
<p></p>
</br>35 O that I had someone listening to me,
@@citzThat according to my signature the Almighty himself would answer me!
@@citzOr that the individual in the case at law with me had written a document itself!
<p></p>
</br>36 Surely upon my shoulder I would carry it;
@@citzI would bind it around me like a grand crown.
<p></p>
</br>37 The number of my steps I would tell him;
@@citzLike a leader I would approach him.
<p></p>
</br>38 If against me my own ground would cry for aid,
@@citzAnd together its furrows themselves would weep;
<p></p>
</br>39 If its fruitage I have eaten without money,
@@citzAnd the soul of its owners I have caused to pant,
<p></p>
</br>40 Instead of wheat let the thorny weed go forth,
@@citzAnd instead of barley stinking weeds.”
<p></p>
The words of Job have come to an end.
