<p></p>
</br>30 The very waters keep themselves hidden as by stone,
@@citzAnd the surface of the watery deep makes itself compact.
<p></p>
</br>31 Can you tie fast the bonds of the Ki´mah constellation,
@@citzOr can you loosen the very cords of the Ke´sil constellation?
<p></p>
</br>32 Can you bring forth the Maz´za·roth constellation in its appointed time?
@@citzAnd as for the Ash constellation alongside its sons, can you conduct them?
<p></p>
</br>33 Have you come to know the statutes of the heavens,
@@citzOr could you put its authority in the earth?
<p></p>
</br>34 Can you raise your voice even to the cloud,
@@citzSo that a heaving mass of water itself may cover you?
<p></p>
</br>35 Can you send forth lightnings that they may go
@@citzAnd say to you, ‘Here we are!’?
<p></p>
</br>36 Who put wisdom in the cloud layers,
@@citzOr who gave understanding to the sky phenomenon?
<p></p>
</br>37 Who can exactly number the clouds in wisdom,
@@citzOr the water jars of heaven—who can tip [them] over,
<p></p>
</br>38 When the dust pours out as into a molten mass,
@@citzAnd the clods of earth themselves get stuck together?
<p></p>
</br>39 Can you hunt prey for a lion itself
@@citzAnd can you satisfy the lively appetite of young lions,
<p></p>
</br>40 When they crouch in the hiding places,
@@citz[Or] keep lying in the covert for an ambush?
<p></p>
</br>41 Who prepares for the raven its food
@@citzWhen its own young ones cry to God for help,
@@citz[When] they keep wandering about because there is nothing to eat?
@@libJob 
</br>39 :
</br>1 -
</br>30 
<p></p>
</br>1 “Have you come to know the appointed time for the mountain goats of the crag to give birth?
@@citzDo you observe just when the hinds bring forth with birth pangs?
<p></p>
</br>2 Do you count the lunar months that they fulfill,
@@citzOr have you come to know the appointed time that they give birth?
<p></p>
</br>3 They bow down when they cast forth their young ones,
@@citz[When] they get rid of their pangs.
<p></p>
</br>4 Their sons become robust, they get big in the open field;
@@citzThey actually go forth and do not return to them.
<p></p>
</br>5 Who sent forth the zebra free,
@@citzAnd who loosened the very bands of the wild ass,
<p></p>
</br>6 Whose house I have appointed the desert plain
@@citzAnd whose dwelling places the salt country?
<p></p>
</br>7 It laughs at the turmoil of a town;
@@citzThe noises of a stalker it does not hear.
<p></p>
</br>8 It explores mountains for its pasturage
@@citzAnd after every sort of green plant it seeks.
<p></p>
</br>9 Does a wild bull want to serve you,
@@citzOr will it spend the night by your manger?
<p></p>
</br>10 Will you bind a wild bull fast with its ropes in the furrow,
@@citzOr will it harrow low plains after you?
<p></p>
</br>11 Will you trust in it because its power is abundant,
@@citzAnd will you leave your toil to it?
<p></p>
</br>12 Will you rely on it that it will bring back your seed
@@citzAnd that it will gather to your threshing floor?
<p></p>
</br>13 Has the wing of the female ostrich flapped joyously,
@@citzOr [has she] the pinions of a stork and the plumage?
<p></p>
</br>14 For she leaves her eggs to the earth itself
@@citzAnd in the dust she keeps them warm,
<p></p>
</br>15 And she forgets that some foot may crush them
@@citzOr even a wild beast of the field may tread on them.
<p></p>
</br>16 She does treat her sons roughly, as if not hers—
@@citzIn vain is her toil [because she has] no dread.
<p></p>
</br>17 For God has made her forget wisdom,
@@citzAnd he has not given her a share in understanding.
<p></p>
</br>18 At the time she flaps [her wings] on high,
@@citzShe laughs at the horse and at its rider.
<p></p>
</br>19 Can you give to the horse mightiness?
@@citzCan you clothe its neck with a rustling mane?
<p></p>
</br>20 Can you cause it to leap like a locust?
@@citzThe dignity of its snorting is frightful.
<p></p>
</br>21 It paws in the low plain and exults in power;
@@citzIt goes forth to meet armor.
<p></p>
</br>22 It laughs at dread, and is not terrified;
@@citzNor does it turn back on account of a sword.
<p></p>
</br>23 Against it a quiver rattles,
@@citzThe blade of a spear and a javelin.
<p></p>
</br>24 With pounding and excitement it swallows up the earth,
@@citzAnd it does not believe that it is the sound of a horn.
<p></p>
</br>25 As soon as the horn blows it says Aha!
@@citzAnd from far off it smells the battle,
@@citzThe uproar of chiefs and the war cry.
<p></p>
</br>26 Is it owing to your understanding that the falcon soars up,
@@citzThat it spreads its wings to the south wind?
<p></p>
</br>27 Or is it at your order that an eagle flies upward
@@citzAnd that it builds its nest high up,
<p></p>
</br>28 That on a crag it resides and stays during the night
@@citzUpon the tooth of a crag and an inaccessible place?
<p></p>
</br>29 From there it has to search for food;
@@citzFar into the distance its eyes keep looking.
<p></p>
</br>30 And its young ones themselves keep sipping up blood;
@@citzAnd where the slain are, there it is.”
