</br>24 
<p></p>
</br>1 And Jehovah proceeded to answer Job and say:
<p></p>
</br>2 “Should there be any contending of a faultfinder with the Almighty?
@@citpLet the reprover of God himself answer it.”
<p></p>
</br>3 And Job went on to answer Jehovah and say:
<p></p>
</br>4 “Look! I have become of little account.
@@citzWhat shall I reply to you?
@@citzMy hand I have put over my mouth.
<p></p>
</br>5 Once have I spoken, and I will not answer;
@@citzAnd twice, and I will add nothing.”
<p></p>
</br>6 And Jehovah went on to answer Job out of the windstorm and say:
<p></p>
</br>7 “Gird up your loins, please, like an able-bodied man;
@@citzI shall question you, and you inform me.
<p></p>
</br>8 Really, will you invalidate my justice?
@@citzWill you pronounce me wicked in order that you may be in the right?
<p></p>
</br>9 Or do you have an arm like that of the [true] God,
@@citzAnd with a voice like his can you make it thunder?
<p></p>
</br>10 Deck yourself, please, with superiority and highness;
@@citzAnd with dignity and splendor may you clothe yourself.
<p></p>
</br>11 Let flow the furious outbursts of your anger,
@@citzAnd see every one haughty and bring him low.
<p></p>
</br>12 See every one haughty, humble him,
@@citzAnd tread down the wicked right where they are.
<p></p>
</br>13 Hide them together in the dust,
@@citzBind their very faces in the hidden place,
<p></p>
</br>14 And I, even I, shall commend you,
@@citzBecause your right hand can save you.
<p></p>
</br>15 Here, now, is Be·he´moth that I have made as well as you.
@@citzGreen grass it eats just as a bull does.
<p></p>
</br>16 Here, now, its power is in its hips,
@@citzAnd its dynamic energy in the tendons of its belly.
<p></p>
</br>17 It bends down its tail like a cedar;
@@citzThe sinews of its thighs are interwoven.
<p></p>
</br>18 Its bones are tubes of copper;
@@citzIts strong bones are like wrought-iron rods.
<p></p>
</br>19 It is the beginning of the ways of God;
@@citzIts Maker can bring near his sword.
<p></p>
</br>20 For the mountains themselves bear their produce for it,
@@citzAnd all the wild beasts of the field themselves play there.
<p></p>
</br>21 Under the thorny lotus trees it lies down,
@@citzIn the concealed place of reeds and the swampy place.
<p></p>
</br>22 The thorny lotus trees keep it blocked off with their shadow;
@@citzThe poplars of the torrent valley surround it.
<p></p>
</br>23 If the river acts violently, it does not run in panic.
@@citzIt is confident, although the Jordan should burst forth against its mouth.
<p></p>
</br>24 Before its eyes can anyone take it?
@@citzWith snares can anyone bore [its] nose?
